President Uhuru Kenyatta and Opposition leader Raila Odinga are said to be holding a meeting at Harambee House in Nairobi. Details are scanty but the two are expected to address the press together at the Office of the President. State House Spokesman Manoah Esipisu said Raila will address reporters before Uhuru and that they will not take questions. Raila is with people including his daughter Winnie and Suna East MP Junet Mohamed, who is the electionals director of Raila's ODM party. There are indications that he and Uhuru have struck a deal to pull their troops together to deal with the issues Kenya is facing. Sources say Friday's meeting is a culmination of informal meetings that have been taking place behind the scenes since Raila swore himself in as the 'People's president'. Related: [VIDEO] Raila oath will give equal footing for talks with Uhuru - MP Nyamita State House had announced that the President would hold a media event at 11am on Friday. Following the disputed August 8, 2017 presidential election and the Nasa chief's self-inauguration, there has been pressure for the two leaders to talk. The United States and other countries called for dialogue after Raila refused to recognise Uhuru as the legitimate President. Meanwhile, the Opposition leader will met US Secretary of State Rex Tillerson this evening. According to the Foreign Affairs ministry, Tillerson's itinerary did not including Raila or the Opposition. Read: US Secretary of State to discuss democracy, press freedom with Uhuru Click here for the latest political news  